explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro performs the parameter check(s) at the start of the function. Its expansion determines whether the check is a no-op in some builds, issues logging, returns/aborts, or otherwise has side effects. To decide if the check(s) are dead (i.e. removable without changing behaviour) you must see the macro definition and any conditional compilation around it.

OS_ObjectIdFindByName: The function called to do the work. You must know whether it has observable side effects (e.g. writes *var_id, modifies global state, logs, etc.) or is pure/unused. If its call has no effect its removal could be deemed dead — conversely, if it updates output parameters or global state its call is necessary.

OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR: The constant passed into OS_ObjectIdFindByName can affect behavior inside that function (selection of object table, side effects). Its value or conditional definitions may change whether the call is meaningful.

osal_id_t: The type of the out-parameter var_id. The typedef (and any qualifiers like volatile) affects whether writing to *var_id is observable; this influences whether the assignment/write performed by OS_ObjectIdFindByName matters to program behaviour.

int32: The return type of the function and of OS_ObjectIdFindByName. Knowing its exact typedef and any special semantics (e.g. mapped to an enum, or used with specific error-code semantics) helps determine whether returning the value is observable behaviour.

OS_printf: Appears in the static call graph for the target path (likely used by OS_CHECK_POINTER or error handling). Logging is observable behaviour; if the parameter-check or call triggers OS_printf, removing that logging would change behaviour. Therefore the definition/usage of OS_printf (and whether it is compiled out) must be known.
